<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
	ws-review-triple-integrals.ptx
	Section 0 (Multivariable Calculus Review), worksheet R4:
	Triple Integrals — over a box, cylindrical coordinates, and spherical
	coordinates.

	CONVENTION: this worksheet follows the STANDARD spherical convention
	(sec_cylindrical_spherical, as of Task B5a): varphi is the polar angle,
	measured down from the +z-axis, 0 <= varphi <= pi, so
	dV = rho^2 sin(varphi) drho dtheta dvarphi. This matches most other
	textbooks, CAS, and online homework systems. The book and the notes
	agree per checklists/worksheet-conventions.md.

	Authored to the SHARED worksheet conventions: paired
	component="stu"/"key" reading checks and exercises; one True/False
	misconception check; one read-along TikZ spherical-coordinates diagram.
	Standard notation; no new macros. Book concepts tracked, example
	equations NOT reused.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-review-triple-integrals">
	<title>Review: Triple Integrals</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>Evaluate a triple integral over a rectangular box.</li>
			<li>Set up a triple integral over a solid by integrating in <m>z</m> first, then over its shadow in the <m>xy</m>-plane.</li>
			<li>Convert to cylindrical coordinates, with <m>dV = r\,dz\,dr\,d\theta</m>.</li>
			<li>Convert to spherical coordinates, with <m>dV = \rho^2\sin\varphi\,d\rho\,d\theta\,d\varphi</m>.</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 1: Triple integrals over a box
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>I. One more dimension.</alert></p>

		<p>
			A triple integral <m>\iiint_D f(x,y,z)\,dV</m> accumulates a
			density over a solid region <m>D</m>, just as a double integral
			accumulates over a plane region. Over a rectangular box it is three
			nested single-variable integrals, evaluated from the inside out.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 1 -->
		<p component="stu">
			A triple integral over a box is evaluated as <fillin characters="6"/>
			<nbsp/>nested integrals; the innermost is taken while the other two
			variables are held <fillin characters="9"/>. Over a rectangular box,
			all six possible orders of integration give the
			<fillin characters="5"/> <nbsp/>value.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			A triple integral over a box is evaluated as
			<m>\underline{\textbf{three}}</m> nested integrals; the innermost is
			taken while the other two variables are held
			<m>\underline{\textbf{constant}}</m>. Over a rectangular box, all six
			possible orders of integration give the
			<m>\underline{\textbf{same}}</m> value.
		</p>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 2: Over a box
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>II. Over a box.</alert></p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.25in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate
					<m>\displaystyle\int_0^1\!\int_0^2\!\int_0^3 xyz \, dz \, dy \, dx</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate
					<m>\displaystyle\int_0^1\!\int_0^2\!\int_0^3 xyz \, dz \, dy \, dx</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Integrate outward, one variable at a time:
					<md>
						\int_0^3 xyz\,dz = xy\left[\frac{z^2}{2}\right]_0^3
						= \frac{9}{2}xy,
					</md>
					<md>
						\int_0^2 \frac{9}{2}xy\,dy
						= \frac{9}{2}x\left[\frac{y^2}{2}\right]_0^2 = 9x,
						\qquad
						\int_0^1 9x\,dx = \frac{9}{2}.
					</md>
					(Because the integrand factors as <m>x\cdot y\cdot z</m> over a
					box, this also equals
					<m>\left(\int_0^1 x\,dx\right)\!\left(\int_0^2 y\,dy\right)\!\left(\int_0^3 z\,dz\right)</m>.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><alert>Your turn.</alert></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					<ol>
						<li>Evaluate <m>\displaystyle\iiint_B (x + y + z)\, dV</m>, where <m>B = [0,1]\times[0,1]\times[0,2]</m>.</li>
						<li>In one sentence, what does <m>\displaystyle\iiint_D 1\, dV</m> compute for a solid <m>D</m>?</li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					<ol>
						<li>Evaluate <m>\displaystyle\iiint_B (x + y + z)\, dV</m>, where <m>B = [0,1]\times[0,1]\times[0,2]</m>.</li>
						<li>In one sentence, what does <m>\displaystyle\iiint_D 1\, dV</m> compute for a solid <m>D</m>?</li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<ol>
						<li>
							<md>
								\int_0^2\!\int_0^1\!\int_0^1 (x+y+z)\,dx\,dy\,dz
								= \int_0^2\!\int_0^1 \left(\tfrac12 + y + z\right) dy\,dz
							</md>
							<md>
								= \int_0^2 \left(1 + z\right) dz
								= \left[z + \tfrac{z^2}{2}\right]_0^2 = 4.
							</md>
						</li>
						<li>
							<m>\displaystyle\iiint_D 1\, dV</m> is the
							<term>volume</term> of the solid <m>D</m>.
						</li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 3: Cylindrical coordinates
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>III. Cylindrical coordinates.</alert></p>

		<p>
			Cylindrical coordinates are just polar coordinates in the
			<m>xy</m>-plane, carrying <m>z</m> along unchanged:
			<m>x = r\cos\theta</m>, <m>y = r\sin\theta</m>, <m>z = z</m>. The
			volume element is the polar area element times <m>dz</m>,
			<md>
				dV = r\,dz\,dr\,d\theta,
			</md>
			so the same <m>r</m> we could not drop in polar carries over. Reach
			for cylindrical when the solid has an axis of symmetry along the
			<m>z</m>-axis.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 2 -->
		<p component="stu">
			In cylindrical coordinates <m>x^2+y^2</m> becomes
			<fillin characters="4"/> <nbsp/>and the volume element is
			<m>dV = </m> <fillin characters="12"/>. These coordinates are the
			natural choice when the solid is symmetric about the
			<fillin characters="6"/>-axis.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			In cylindrical coordinates <m>x^2+y^2</m> becomes
			<m>\underline{r^2}</m> and the volume element is
			<m>dV = \underline{r\,dz\,dr\,d\theta}</m>. These coordinates
			are the natural choice when the solid is symmetric about the
			<m>\underline{\textbf{z}}</m>-axis.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the volume of the solid bounded below by the plane
					<m>z = 0</m> and above by the paraboloid <m>z = 4 - x^2 - y^2</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the volume of the solid bounded below by the plane
					<m>z = 0</m> and above by the paraboloid <m>z = 4 - x^2 - y^2</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The paraboloid meets <m>z=0</m> where <m>x^2+y^2 = 4</m>, a disk
					of radius <m>2</m>; in cylindrical the cap is
					<m>z = 4 - r^2</m>. So
					<md>
						V = \int_0^{2\pi}\!\int_0^2\!\int_0^{4-r^2} r\,dz\,dr\,d\theta
						= \int_0^{2\pi}\!\int_0^2 (4-r^2)\,r\,dr\,d\theta
					</md>
					<md>
						= \int_0^{2\pi}\left[2r^2 - \frac{r^4}{4}\right]_0^2 d\theta
						= \int_0^{2\pi} 4\,d\theta = 8\pi.
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 4: Spherical coordinates
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>IV. Spherical coordinates.</alert></p>

		<p>
			Spherical coordinates locate a point by its distance
			<m>\rho \ge 0</m> from the origin and two angles.
		</p>

		<p>
			<alert>Convention (read carefully).</alert> We measure the angle
			<m>\varphi</m> <em>down from the <m>z</m>-axis</em> (the
			<term>polar angle</term>, like the angle from the north pole), so
			<m>0 \le \varphi \le \pi</m>, and <m>\theta</m> is the usual angle in
			the <m>xy</m>-plane. With that choice,
			<md>
				x = \rho\sin\varphi\cos\theta,\quad
				y = \rho\sin\varphi\sin\theta,\quad
				z = \rho\cos\varphi,
			</md>
			<md>
				dV = \rho^2\sin\varphi\,d\rho\,d\theta\,d\varphi.
			</md>
			This is the convention used by most textbooks, computer algebra
			systems, and online homework systems. (A caution for physics: there
			the letters <m>\theta</m> and <m>\varphi</m> are usually swapped, so
			check which angle is which before applying a formula.)
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="ws-r4-fig-spherical">
			<caption>Spherical coordinates: <m>\rho</m> is the
				distance to <m>P</m>, <m>\theta</m> is measured in the
				<m>xy</m>-plane, and <m>\varphi</m> is measured down from the
				<m>z</m>-axis.</caption>
			<image width="52%">
				<shortdescription>A point P in space with its position vector from the origin. The angle theta is shown in the horizontal plane between the x-axis and the shadow of the vector; the angle phi is shown between the positive z-axis and the vector; rho labels the length of the vector.</shortdescription>
				<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.6,>=stealth,
		x={(-0.72cm,-0.42cm)}, y={(1cm,-0.28cm)}, z={(0cm,1cm)}]
	\coordinate (O) at (0,0,0);
	\coordinate (P) at (1.075,1.281,1.992);
	\coordinate (Pxy) at (1.075,1.281,0);
	% axes (z drawn vertical so phi reads as the angle down from the z-axis)
	\draw[->] (0,0,0) -- (2,0,0) node[anchor=east] {$x$};
	\draw[->] (0,0,0) -- (0,2.4,0) node[anchor=west] {$y$};
	\draw[->] (0,0,0) -- (0,0,2.5) node[anchor=south] {$z$};
	% projection and vertical drop
	\draw[dashed, gray] (O) -- (Pxy);
	\draw[dashed, gray] (Pxy) -- (P);
	% position vector
	\draw[very thick, blue, ->] (O) -- (P);
	\node[blue, anchor=south west] at (P) {$P$};
	\node[blue] at (0.75,0.80,0.85) {$\rho$};
	% theta arc in the xy-plane, from the x-axis to the shadow of P
	\draw[red, ->, smooth] plot coordinates {(0.55,0,0) (0.537,0.119,0) (0.498,0.233,0) (0.436,0.335,0) (0.354,0.421,0)};
	\node[red] at (0.62,0.30,0) {$\theta$};
	% phi arc from the +z-axis down to the vector (the polar angle)
	\draw[teal, ->, smooth] plot coordinates {(0,0,0.85) (0.095,0.113,0.837) (0.187,0.223,0.799) (0.273,0.326,0.736) (0.351,0.419,0.651)};
	\node[teal] at (0.23,0.28,1.0) {$\varphi$};
	\node[anchor=north] at (Pxy) {\footnotesize shadow of $P$};
	\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<!-- reading-check pair 3 -->
		<p component="stu">
			In this course <m>\varphi</m> is measured from the positive
			<fillin characters="4"/>-axis, so it ranges from
			<fillin characters="6"/> <nbsp/>to <m>\pi</m>, and the spherical
			volume element is <m>dV = </m> <fillin characters="22"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			In this course <m>\varphi</m> is measured from the positive
			<m>\underline{\textbf{z}}</m>-axis, so it ranges from
			<m>\underline{\textbf{0}}</m> to <m>\pi</m>, and the spherical
			volume element is
			<m>dV = \underline{\rho^2\sin\varphi\,d\rho\,d\theta\,d\varphi}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use spherical coordinates to find the volume of a ball of
					radius <m>2</m> centered at the origin.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use spherical coordinates to find the volume of a ball of
					radius <m>2</m> centered at the origin.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The ball is <m>0 \le \rho \le 2</m>, <m>0 \le \theta \le 2\pi</m>,
					<m>0 \le \varphi \le \pi</m>. The integral separates:
					<md>
						V = \int_0^{\pi}\!\int_0^{2\pi}\!\int_0^2
						\rho^2\sin\varphi\,d\rho\,d\theta\,d\varphi
						= \left(\int_0^2\!\rho^2 d\rho\right)
						  \left(\int_0^{2\pi}\!d\theta\right)
						  \left(\int_0^{\pi}\!\sin\varphi\,d\varphi\right).
					</md>
					These are <m>\dfrac{8}{3}</m>, <m>2\pi</m>, and
					<m>\big[-\cos\varphi\big]_0^{\pi} = 2</m>, so
					<md>
						V = \frac{8}{3}\cdot 2\pi \cdot 2 = \frac{32\pi}{3},
					</md>
					exactly the classic <m>\frac{4}{3}\pi r^3</m> with <m>r=2</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<!-- misconception check: single exercise, solution instructor-only -->
		<exercise xml:id="ws-r4-tf-spherical">
			<statement>
				<p>
					<alert>True or False.</alert> In spherical coordinates,
					<m>dV = \rho^2\,d\rho\,d\theta\,d\varphi</m>. Explain.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					<term>False.</term> An angular factor is missing. With
					<m>\varphi</m> the polar angle (measured from the <m>z</m>-axis),
					<m>dV = \rho^2\sin\varphi\,d\rho\,d\theta\,d\varphi</m>. The lone
					<m>\rho^2</m> is not enough — dropping the <m>\sin\varphi</m> is
					the classic spherical-integral mistake. (Watch out: some books
					measure <m>\varphi</m> from the <m>xy</m>-plane instead, giving
					<m>\cos\varphi</m>; always check the convention.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 5: A mass application + looking ahead
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>V. Mass of a solid.</alert></p>

		<p>
			Replacing the integrand <m>1</m> (which gives volume) by a
			<term>density</term> <m>\delta(x,y,z)</m> turns a triple integral
			into a <term>mass</term>: <m>M = \iiint_D \delta\, dV</m>. When the
			density depends only on distance from the origin, spherical
			coordinates are ideal.
		</p>

		<!-- application (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A solid ball of radius <m>1</m> has density equal to the
					distance from its center, <m>\delta = \rho</m>. Find its total
					mass.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A solid ball of radius <m>1</m> has density equal to the
					distance from its center, <m>\delta = \rho</m>. Find its total
					mass.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					With <m>\delta = \rho</m> and
					<m>dV = \rho^2\sin\varphi\,d\rho\,d\theta\,d\varphi</m>, the
					integrand is <m>\rho\cdot\rho^2\sin\varphi = \rho^3\sin\varphi</m>:
					<md>
						M = \int_0^{\pi}\!\int_0^{2\pi}\!\int_0^1
						\rho^3\sin\varphi\,d\rho\,d\theta\,d\varphi
						= \frac{1}{4}\cdot 2\pi \cdot 2 = \pi.
					</md>
					The mass is <m>\pi</m>. Because the density grows with
					<m>\rho</m>, most of the mass sits in the outer shells rather
					than near the center.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<p>
				<alert>Looking ahead.</alert> That completes the review of the
				multivariable calculus MA 301 builds on — functions and their
				graphs, partial derivatives, and now single, double, and triple
				integrals. From here the course turns to its real subject,
				<term>vector analysis</term>: vector fields, line and surface
				integrals, and the theorems of Green, Stokes, and Gauss that tie
				derivatives and integrals together in higher dimensions.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>

</worksheet>
